{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}
{{essay-like|date=May 2018}}
{{sections|date=June 2018}}
}}
[[Puerto Rico]] is and has been in economic crisis for a very long time due to the unpayable debt the island has. As of 2015 it is 72 billion dollars.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ora|first=Bannan, Natasha Lycia|date=2016|title=Puerto Rico's Odious Debt: The Economic Crisis of Colonialism|url=https://academicworks.cuny.edu/clr/vol19/iss2/5/|journal=City University of New York Law Review|language=en|volume=19|issue=2}}</ref> The mounting debt has caused a lot of damage to the society in question. Cutbacks on a lot of necessities in the island have caused a health care problem. In the mental health care, the problem grows bigger as people find themselves unemployed or with lack of good jobs a lot of people have fled the island,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iniciativacomunitaria.org/homeless-drug-addicted-more-vulnerable-amid-puerto-rico-debt-crisis/?lang=en|title=Iniciativa Comunitaria {{!}} Homeless, drug-addicted more vulnerable amid Puerto Rico debt crisis|website=www.iniciativacomunitaria.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> causing a lack of professionals.

With a large amount of people migrating out of Puerto Rico to find better jobs an opportunity, professionals and students are lacking. This greatly impacts the mental healthcare of the public, with a lack of people and funds to pay professionals, leaving those who are in need, to suffer. This leaves the mental health care specialized areas severely limited.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jiménez|first=J.|last2=Rivera|first2=D.|last3=Benítez|first3=P.|last4=Tarrats|first4=H.|last5=Ramos|first5=A.|date=2013-09-01|title=Integrating Mental Health Services into a General Hospital in Puerto Rico|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10880-012-9352-x|journal=Journal of Clinical Psychology in Medical Settings|language=en|volume=20|issue=3|pages=294–301|doi=10.1007/s10880-012-9352-x|issn=1068-9583}}</ref>

The suicide rate in Puerto Rico is high with it being one of the top 15 causes of death in the island.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Vera|first=Mildred|last2=Reyes-Rabanillo|first2=María L|last3=Huertas|first3=Sarah|last4=Juarbe|first4=Deborah|last5=Pérez-Pedrogo|first5=Coralee|last6=Huertas|first6=Aracelis|last7=Peña|first7=Marisol|date=2011-03-11|title=Suicide ideation, plans, and attempts among general practice patients with chronic health conditions in Puerto Rico |journal=[[International Journal of General Medicine]]|volume=4|pages=197–205|doi=10.2147/IJGM.S17156 |pmc=3068880|pmid=21475631}}</ref> A study shows that people with chronic illnesses are likely to think about, and attempt suicide. 25% of all suicides attempts are committed by people with chronic illness.<ref name=":0" />

[[Suicide ideation]] is high among people with [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] and active depression symptoms.<ref name=":0" /> Socioeconomic issues were linked to increased suicide attempts or ideation by education, those without a college degree were more likely to think about or commit suicide.<ref name=":0" />

The professionals in charge of treating mental illness lack training in suicide prevention is also a problem.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jiménez Chafey|first=Maria|last2=Serra Taylor|first2=José|last3=Irizarry Robles|first3=Carol|date=July 2013|title=University Mental Health Professionals in Puerto Rico: Suicide Experiences, Attitudes, Practices, and Intervention Skills|url=http://web.b.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=0&sid=5a29df02-a2dc-40cd-a7a9-2ee8a5fa29f6%40sessionmgr101&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#AN=89440163&db=a9h|journal=Journal of College Student Psychotherapy|volume=27|pages=238–253|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>

In Puerto Rico, 60% of children live in [[poverty]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsismybusiness.com/children-living-poverty/|title=Study: Some 60% of P.R.’s children living in poverty {{!}} News is my Business|last=admin|website=newsismybusiness.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>

According to research and statistics, men tend to lash out in violence when unemployed. It threatens their masculinity and to re-ensure power and control, they would physically and mentally abuse their wife or significant others.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Warren|first=Alice E. Colón|date=2003|title=Puerto Rico: Feminism and Feminist Studies|jstor=3594704|journal=Gender and Society|volume=17|issue=5|pages=664–690}}</ref>

Thereafter, women and men both lack the potential and qualification to retain a job. The stress of experiencing poverty and the lack of financial support impacts executive functions. In the case of poverty, people are prone to experience depression, stress, [[addiction]], low self-esteem and suicide. As mentioned above, suicide records in Puerto Rico reached a high 25% before the 20th century. In the aftermath of [[Hurricane Maria]], researchers and ‘The Commission for the  Prevention of Suicide’ reported an 16% increase. Approximately, a suicide per day since 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/puerto-rico-mental-health-hurricane-maria-us-780062|title=Doctors in Puerto Rico are blaming Hurricane Maria for the spike in suicide rates|date=2018-01-13|work=Newsweek|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en}}</ref>

Daniel C. Marston, a cognitive and behavioral psychologist, conducted a study on the ‘Neurobehavioral and psychological effect on poverty’. Marston's findings distinguish the differences poverty has on adults, children, families and new moms. As stated, the psychological effects with poverty causes depression, anxiety and suicidal thoughts. Marston's study states that adults in poverty display higher levels of withdrawal symptoms, somatic complaints and pervasive negative thinking. Adults are impacted by feeling worry and anxious about what how handle the situation. In contrast, children are impacted by feeling a sense of helplessness and lack of control. Children are more likely to experience developmental delays, attention problem and disciplinary problems.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.apa.org/pi/ses/resources/indicator/2013/01/poverty-behaviors.aspx|title=Neurobehavioral effects of poverty|website=www.apa.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>

In addition, factors such as  poverty, lack of resources, malnutrition and environmental factors significantly impacts a fetus physical development and executive functions. They are in higher risks to develop [[Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADHD]] and [[autism]]. Newborn babies are troubled by lack of proper functions, such as communicating and socializing.<ref name=":1" />

On the other hand, denial may not be the case for all Puerto Ricans since the economic crisis effects most poverty and minority individuals. Lack of public resources affects both the psychologist and patient. According to the welfare system, they will be responsible to cover some of the many visits, medication and tests. Leaving unemployed or lower class Puerto Ricans responsible to pay out of pocket for further services. To top it off, beginning 2018, [[Ricardo Rosselló|Governor Ricardo Rosselló]] enforced work/employment requirement for welfare recipients on the island, presenting great challenges for Puerto Ricans, when more than 48% of the island's people live below the federally defined [[poverty line]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fee.org/articles/puerto-ricos-man-made-disaster-might-be-worse-than-the-hurricane/|title=Puerto Rico's Man-Made Disaster Might Be Worse than the Hurricane {{!}} Daniel J. Mitchell|date=2017-10-16|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en-US}}</ref>

The first epidemiological study the status of mental health in Puerto Rico in 1985, shows that 165,497 people suffer from serious conditions in a population of 3,187,671. Many of the participants suffered from mental, emotional and behavioral conditions, while many remained silent. Quoting the research, facilities accepted and treated those with serious and disabling conditions and not to those who, despite also suffering from mental illnesses, are still considered “functional.” One out of every 10 Puerto Rican, since 1985, have suffered from [[anxiety]] and [[panic disorder]], [[mood disorders]] and depression. Some experienced a combination of disorders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/english/english/nota/criticalstateofmentalhealthinpuertorico-2281421/|title=Critical State of Mental Health in Puerto Rico|date=2017-01-16|work=El Nuevo Dia|access-date=2018-05-11|language=es-pr}}</ref>

Daniel C. Marston concluded, “lack of access to appropriate care due to economic crisis, traditionally identified as in main reason why people in poverty do not receive services to help address neuro-behavioral problems.<ref name=":1" />” Overall the economic crisis in Puerto Rico negatively affects all aspects of life but the mental healthcare system is an important aspect of this.

